3/*++
4/* NAME
5/* postmap 1
6/* SUMMARY
7/* Postfix lookup table management
8/* SYNOPSIS
9/* .fi
10/* \fBpostmap\fR [\fB-NbfhimnoprsuUvw\fR] [\fB-c \fIconfig_dir\fR]
11/* [\fB-d \fIkey\fR] [\fB-q \fIkey\fR]
12/* [\fIfile_type\fR:]\fIfile_name\fR ...
13/* DESCRIPTION
14/* The \fBpostmap\fR(1) command creates or queries one or more Postfix
15/* lookup tables, or updates an existing one. The input and output
16/* file formats are expected to be compatible with:
17/*
18/* .nf
19/* \fBmakemap \fIfile_type\fR \fIfile_name\fR < \fIfile_name\fR
20/* .fi
21/*
22/* If the result files do not exist they will be created with the
23/* same group and other read permissions as their source file.
24/*
25/* While the table update is in progress, signal delivery is
26/* postponed, and an exclusive, advisory, lock is placed on the
27/* entire table, in order to avoid surprises in spectator
28/* processes.
29/* INPUT FILE FORMAT
30/* .ad
31/* .fi
32/* The format of a lookup table input file is as follows:
33/* .IP \(bu
34/* A table entry has the form
35/* .sp
36/* .nf
37/* \fIkey\fR whitespace \fIvalue\fR
38/* .fi
39/* .IP \(bu
40/* Empty lines and whitespace-only lines are ignored, as
41/* are lines whose first non-whitespace character is a `#'.
42/* .IP \(bu
43/* A logical line starts with non-whitespace text. A line that
44/* starts with whitespace continues a logical line.
45/* .PP
46/* The \fIkey\fR and \fIvalue\fR are processed as is, except that
47/* surrounding white space is stripped off. Unlike with Postfix alias
48/* databases, quotes cannot be used to protect lookup keys that contain
49/* special characters such as `#' or whitespace.
50/*
51/* By default the lookup key is mapped to lowercase to make
52/* the lookups case insensitive; as of Postfix 2.3 this case
53/* folding happens only with tables whose lookup keys are
54/* fixed-case strings such as btree:, dbm: or hash:. With
55/* earlier versions, the lookup key is folded even with tables
56/* where a lookup field can match both upper and lower case
57/* text, such as regexp: and pcre:. This resulted in loss of
58/* information with $\fInumber\fR substitutions.
59/* COMMAND-LINE ARGUMENTS
60/* .ad
61/* .fi
62/* .IP \fB-b\fR
63/* Enable message body query mode. When reading lookup keys
64/* from standard input with "\fB-q -\fR", process the input
65/* as if it is an email message in RFC 2822 format. Each line
66/* of body content becomes one lookup key.
67/* .sp
68/* By default, the \fB-b\fR option starts generating lookup
69/* keys at the first non-header line, and stops when the end
70/* of the message is reached.
71/* To simulate \fBbody_checks\fR(5) processing, enable MIME
72/* parsing with \fB-m\fR. With this, the \fB-b\fR option
73/* generates no body-style lookup keys for attachment MIME
74/* headers and for attached message/* headers.
75/* .sp
76/* NOTE: with "smtputf8_enable = yes", the \fB-b\fR option
77/* option disables UTF-8 syntax checks on query keys and
78/* lookup results. Specify the \fB-U\fR option to force UTF-8
79/* syntax checks anyway.
80/* .sp
81/* This feature is available in Postfix version 2.6 and later.
82/* .IP "\fB-c \fIconfig_dir\fR"
83/* Read the \fBmain.cf\fR configuration file in the named directory
84/* instead of the default configuration directory.
85/* .IP "\fB-d \fIkey\fR"
86/* Search the specified maps for \fIkey\fR and remove one entry per map.
87/* The exit status is zero when the requested information was found.
88/*
89/* If a key value of \fB-\fR is specified, the program reads key
90/* values from the standard input stream. The exit status is zero
91/* when at least one of the requested keys was found.
92/* .IP \fB-f\fR
93/* Do not fold the lookup key to lower case while creating or querying
94/* a table.
95/*
96/* With Postfix version 2.3 and later, this option has no
97/* effect for regular expression tables. There, case folding
98/* is controlled by appending a flag to a pattern.
99/* .IP \fB-h\fR
100/* Enable message header query mode. When reading lookup keys
101/* from standard input with "\fB-q -\fR", process the input
102/* as if it is an email message in RFC 2822 format. Each
103/* logical header line becomes one lookup key. A multi-line
104/* header becomes one lookup key with one or more embedded
105/* newline characters.
106/* .sp
107/* By default, the \fB-h\fR option generates lookup keys until
108/* the first non-header line is reached.
109/* To simulate \fBheader_checks\fR(5) processing, enable MIME
110/* parsing with \fB-m\fR. With this, the \fB-h\fR option also
111/* generates header-style lookup keys for attachment MIME
112/* headers and for attached message/* headers.
113/* .sp
114/* NOTE: with "smtputf8_enable = yes", the \fB-b\fR option
115/* option disables UTF-8 syntax checks on query keys and
116/* lookup results. Specify the \fB-U\fR option to force UTF-8
117/* syntax checks anyway.
118/* .sp
119/* This feature is available in Postfix version 2.6 and later.
120/* .IP \fB-i\fR
121/* Incremental mode. Read entries from standard input and do not
122/* truncate an existing database. By default, \fBpostmap\fR(1) creates
123/* a new database from the entries in \fBfile_name\fR.
124/* .IP \fB-m\fR
125/* Enable MIME parsing with "\fB-b\fR" and "\fB-h\fR".
126/* .sp
127/* This feature is available in Postfix version 2.6 and later.
128/* .IP \fB-N\fR
129/* Include the terminating null character that terminates lookup keys
130/* and values. By default, \fBpostmap\fR(1) does whatever is
131/* the default for
132/* the host operating system.
133/* .IP \fB-n\fR
134/* Don't include the terminating null character that terminates lookup
135/* keys and values. By default, \fBpostmap\fR(1) does whatever
136/* is the default for
137/* the host operating system.
138/* .IP \fB-o\fR
139/* Do not release root privileges when processing a non-root
140/* input file. By default, \fBpostmap\fR(1) drops root privileges
141/* and runs as the source file owner instead.
142/* .IP \fB-p\fR
143/* Do not inherit the file access permissions from the input file
144/* when creating a new file. Instead, create a new file with default
145/* access permissions (mode 0644).
146/* .IP "\fB-q \fIkey\fR"
147/* Search the specified maps for \fIkey\fR and write the first value
148/* found to the standard output stream. The exit status is zero
149/* when the requested information was found.
150/*
151/* If a key value of \fB-\fR is specified, the program reads key
152/* values from the standard input stream and writes one line of
153/* \fIkey value\fR output for each key that was found. The exit
154/* status is zero when at least one of the requested keys was found.
155/* .IP \fB-r\fR
156/* When updating a table, do not complain about attempts to update
157/* existing entries, and make those updates anyway.
158/* .IP \fB-s\fR
159/* Retrieve all database elements, and write one line of
160/* \fIkey value\fR output for each element. The elements are
161/* printed in database order, which is not necessarily the same
162/* as the original input order.
163/* .sp
164/* This feature is available in Postfix version 2.2 and later,
165/* and is not available for all database types.
166/* .IP \fB-u\fR
167/* Disable UTF-8 support. UTF-8 support is enabled by default
168/* when "smtputf8_enable = yes". It requires that keys and
169/* values are valid UTF-8 strings.
170/* .IP \fB-U\fR
171/* With "smtputf8_enable = yes", force UTF-8 syntax checks
172/* with the \fB-b\fR and \fB-h\fR options.
173/* .IP \fB-v\fR
174/* Enable verbose logging for debugging purposes. Multiple \fB-v\fR
175/* options make the software increasingly verbose.
176/* .IP \fB-w\fR
177/* When updating a table, do not complain about attempts to update
178/* existing entries, and ignore those attempts.
179/* .PP
180/* Arguments:
181/* .IP \fIfile_type\fR
182/* The database type. To find out what types are supported, use
183/* the "\fBpostconf -m\fR" command.
184/*
185/* The \fBpostmap\fR(1) command can query any supported file type,
186/* but it can create only the following file types:
187/* .RS
188/* .IP \fBbtree\fR
189/* The output file is a btree file, named \fIfile_name\fB.db\fR.
190/* This is available on systems with support for \fBdb\fR databases.
191/* .IP \fBcdb\fR
192/* The output consists of one file, named \fIfile_name\fB.cdb\fR.
193/* This is available on systems with support for \fBcdb\fR databases.
194/* .IP \fBdbm\fR
195/* The output consists of two files, named \fIfile_name\fB.pag\fR and
196/* \fIfile_name\fB.dir\fR.
197/* This is available on systems with support for \fBdbm\fR databases.
198/* .IP \fBhash\fR
199/* The output file is a hashed file, named \fIfile_name\fB.db\fR.
200/* This is available on systems with support for \fBdb\fR databases.
201/* .IP \fBfail\fR
202/* A table that reliably fails all requests. The lookup table
203/* name is used for logging only. This table exists to simplify
204/* Postfix error tests.
205/* .IP \fBsdbm\fR
206/* The output consists of two files, named \fIfile_name\fB.pag\fR and
207/* \fIfile_name\fB.dir\fR.
208/* This is available on systems with support for \fBsdbm\fR databases.
209/* .PP
210/* When no \fIfile_type\fR is specified, the software uses the database
211/* type specified via the \fBdefault_database_type\fR configuration
212/* parameter.
213/* .RE
214/* .IP \fIfile_name\fR
215/* The name of the lookup table source file when rebuilding a database.
216/* DIAGNOSTICS
217/* Problems are logged to the standard error stream and to
218/* \fBsyslogd\fR(8).
219/* No output means that no problems were detected. Duplicate entries are
220/* skipped and are flagged with a warning.
221/*
222/* \fBpostmap\fR(1) terminates with zero exit status in case of success
223/* (including successful "\fBpostmap -q\fR" lookup) and terminates
224/* with non-zero exit status in case of failure.
225/* ENVIRONMENT
226/* .ad
227/* .fi
228/* .IP \fBMAIL_CONFIG\fR
229/* Directory with Postfix configuration files.
230/* .IP \fBMAIL_VERBOSE\fR
231/* Enable verbose logging for debugging purposes.
232/* CONFIGURATION PARAMETERS
233/* .ad
234/* .fi
235/* The following \fBmain.cf\fR parameters are especially relevant to
236/* this program.
237/* The text below provides only a parameter summary. See
238/* \fBpostconf\fR(5) for more details including examples.
239/* .IP "\fBberkeley_db_create_buffer_size (16777216)\fR"
240/* The per-table I/O buffer size for programs that create Berkeley DB
241/* hash or btree tables.
242/* .IP "\fBberkeley_db_read_buffer_size (131072)\fR"
243/* The per-table I/O buffer size for programs that read Berkeley DB
244/* hash or btree tables.
245/* .IP "\fBconfig_directory (see 'postconf -d' output)\fR"
246/* The default location of the Postfix main.cf and master.cf
247/* configuration files.
248/* .IP "\fBdefault_database_type (see 'postconf -d' output)\fR"
249/* The default database type for use in \fBnewaliases\fR(1), \fBpostalias\fR(1)
250/* and \fBpostmap\fR(1) commands.
251/* .IP "\fBsmtputf8_enable (yes)\fR"
252/* Enable preliminary SMTPUTF8 support for the protocols described
253/* in RFC 6531..6533.
254/* .IP "\fBsyslog_facility (mail)\fR"
255/* The syslog facility of Postfix logging.
256/* .IP "\fBsyslog_name (see 'postconf -d' output)\fR"
257/* The mail system name that is prepended to the process name in syslog
258/* records, so that "smtpd" becomes, for example, "postfix/smtpd".
259/* SEE ALSO
260/* postalias(1), create/update/query alias database
261/* postconf(1), supported database types
262/* postconf(5), configuration parameters
263/* syslogd(8), system logging
264/* README FILES
265/* .ad
266/* .fi
267/* Use "\fBpostconf readme_directory\fR" or
268/* "\fBpostconf html_directory\fR" to locate this information.
269/* .na
270/* .nf
271/* DATABASE_README, Postfix lookup table overview
272/* LICENSE
273/* .ad
274/* .fi
275/* The Secure Mailer license must be distributed with this software.
276/* AUTHOR(S)
277/* Wietse Venema
278/* IBM T.J. Watson Research
279/* P.O. Box 704
280/* Yorktown Heights, NY 10598, USA
281/*
282/* Wietse Venema
283/* Google, Inc.
284/* 111 8th Avenue
285/* New York, NY 10011, USA
286/*--*/

325/* Application-specific. */
326
327#define STR vstring_str
328#define LEN VSTRING_LEN
329
330#define POSTMAP_FLAG_AS_OWNER (1<<0) /* open dest as owner of source */
331#define POSTMAP_FLAG_SAVE_PERM (1<<1) /* copy access permission from source */
332#define POSTMAP_FLAG_HEADER_KEY (1<<2) /* apply to header text */
333#define POSTMAP_FLAG_BODY_KEY (1<<3) /* apply to body text */
334#define POSTMAP_FLAG_MIME_KEY (1<<4) /* enable MIME parsing */
335
336#define POSTMAP_FLAG_HB_KEY (POSTMAP_FLAG_HEADER_KEY | POSTMAP_FLAG_BODY_KEY)
337#define POSTMAP_FLAG_FULL_KEY (POSTMAP_FLAG_BODY_KEY | POSTMAP_FLAG_MIME_KEY)
338#define POSTMAP_FLAG_ANY_KEY (POSTMAP_FLAG_HB_KEY | POSTMAP_FLAG_MIME_KEY)
339
340 /*
341 * MIME Engine call-back state for generating lookup keys from an email
342 * message read from standard input.
343 */
344typedef struct {
345 DICT **dicts; /* map handles */
346 char **maps; /* map names */
347 int map_count; /* yes, indeed */
348 int dict_flags; /* query flags */
349 int header_done; /* past primary header */
350 int found; /* result */
351} POSTMAP_KEY_STATE;
352
353/* postmap - create or update mapping database */
354
355static void postmap(char *map_type, char *path_name, int postmap_flags,
356 int open_flags, int dict_flags)
357{
358 VSTREAM *NOCLOBBER source_fp;
359 VSTRING *line_buffer;
360 MKMAP *mkmap;
361 int lineno;
362 int last_line;
363 char *key;
364 char *value;
365 struct stat st;
366 mode_t saved_mask;
367
368 /*
369 * Initialize.
370 */
371 line_buffer = vstring_alloc(100);
372 if ((open_flags & O_TRUNC) == 0) {
373 /* Incremental mode. */
374 source_fp = VSTREAM_IN;
375 vstream_control(source_fp, CA_VSTREAM_CTL_PATH("stdin"), CA_VSTREAM_CTL_END);
376 } else {
377 /* Create database. */
378 if (strcmp(map_type, DICT_TYPE_PROXY) == 0)
379 msg_fatal("can't create maps via the proxy service");
380 dict_flags |= DICT_FLAG_BULK_UPDATE;
381 if ((source_fp = vstream_fopen(path_name, O_RDONLY, 0)) == 0)
382 msg_fatal("open %s: %m", path_name);
383 }
384 if (fstat(vstream_fileno(source_fp), &st) < 0)
385 msg_fatal("fstat %s: %m", path_name);
386
387 /*
388 * Turn off group/other read permissions as indicated in the source file.
389 */
390 if ((postmap_flags & POSTMAP_FLAG_SAVE_PERM) && S_ISREG(st.st_mode))
391 saved_mask = umask(022 | (~st.st_mode & 077));
392
393 /*
394 * If running as root, run as the owner of the source file, so that the
395 * result shows proper ownership, and so that a bug in postmap does not
396 * allow privilege escalation.
397 */
398 if ((postmap_flags & POSTMAP_FLAG_AS_OWNER) && getuid() == 0
399 && (st.st_uid != geteuid() || st.st_gid != getegid()))
400 set_eugid(st.st_uid, st.st_gid);
401
402 /*
403 * Open the database, optionally create it when it does not exist,
404 * optionally truncate it when it does exist, and lock out any
405 * spectators.
406 */
407 mkmap = mkmap_open(map_type, path_name, open_flags, dict_flags);
408
409 /*
410 * And restore the umask, in case it matters.
411 */
412 if ((postmap_flags & POSTMAP_FLAG_SAVE_PERM) && S_ISREG(st.st_mode))
413 umask(saved_mask);
414
415 /*
416 * Trap "exceptions" so that we can restart a bulk-mode update after a
417 * recoverable error.
418 */
419 for (;;) {
420 if (dict_isjmp(mkmap->dict) != 0
421 && dict_setjmp(mkmap->dict) != 0
422 && vstream_fseek(source_fp, SEEK_SET, 0) < 0)
423 msg_fatal("seek %s: %m", VSTREAM_PATH(source_fp));
424
425 /*
426 * Add records to the database.
427 */
428 last_line = 0;
429 while (readllines(line_buffer, source_fp, &last_line, &lineno)) {
430
431 /*
432 * First some UTF-8 checks sans casefolding.
433 */
434 if ((mkmap->dict->flags & DICT_FLAG_UTF8_ACTIVE)
435 && !allascii(STR(line_buffer))
436 && !valid_utf8_string(STR(line_buffer), LEN(line_buffer))) {
437 msg_warn("%s, line %d: non-UTF-8 input \"%s\""
438 " -- ignoring this line",
439 VSTREAM_PATH(source_fp), lineno, STR(line_buffer));
440 continue;
441 }
442
443 /*
444 * Split on the first whitespace character, then trim leading and
445 * trailing whitespace from key and value.
446 */
447 key = STR(line_buffer);
448 value = key + strcspn(key, CHARS_SPACE);
449 if (*value)
450 *value++ = 0;
451 while (ISSPACE(*value))
452 value++;
453 trimblanks(key, 0)[0] = 0;
454 trimblanks(value, 0)[0] = 0;
455
456 /*
457 * Enforce the "key whitespace value" format. Disallow missing
458 * keys or missing values.
459 */
460 if (*key == 0 || *value == 0) {
461 msg_warn("%s, line %d: expected format: key whitespace value",
462 VSTREAM_PATH(source_fp), lineno);
463 continue;
464 }
465 if (key[strlen(key) - 1] == ':')
466 msg_warn("%s, line %d: record is in \"key: value\" format; is this an alias file?",
467 VSTREAM_PATH(source_fp), lineno);
468
469 /*
470 * Store the value under a case-insensitive key.
471 */
472 mkmap_append(mkmap, key, value);
473 if (mkmap->dict->error)
474 msg_fatal("table %s:%s: write error: %m",
475 mkmap->dict->type, mkmap->dict->name);
476 }
477 break;
478 }
479
480 /*
481 * Close the mapping database, and release the lock.
482 */
483 mkmap_close(mkmap);
484
485 /*
486 * Cleanup. We're about to terminate, but it is a good sanity check.
487 */
488 vstring_free(line_buffer);
489 if (source_fp != VSTREAM_IN)
490 vstream_fclose(source_fp);
491}
492
493/* postmap_body - MIME engine body call-back routine */
494
495static void postmap_body(void *ptr, int unused_rec_type,
496 const char *keybuf,
497 ssize_t unused_len,
498 off_t unused_offset)
499{
500 POSTMAP_KEY_STATE *state = (POSTMAP_KEY_STATE *) ptr;
501 DICT **dicts = state->dicts;
502 char **maps = state->maps;
503 int map_count = state->map_count;
504 int dict_flags = state->dict_flags;
505 const char *map_name;
506 const char *value;
507 int n;
508
509 for (n = 0; n < map_count; n++) {
510 if (dicts[n] == 0)
511 dicts[n] = ((map_name = split_at(maps[n], ':')) != 0 ?
512 dict_open3(maps[n], map_name, O_RDONLY, dict_flags) :
513 dict_open3(var_db_type, maps[n], O_RDONLY, dict_flags));
514 if ((value = dict_get(dicts[n], keybuf)) != 0) {
515 if (*value == 0) {
516 msg_warn("table %s:%s: key %s: empty string result is not allowed",
517 dicts[n]->type, dicts[n]->name, keybuf);
518 msg_warn("table %s:%s should return NO RESULT in case of NOT FOUND",
519 dicts[n]->type, dicts[n]->name);
520 }
521 vstream_printf("%s %s\n", keybuf, value);
522 state->found = 1;
523 break;
524 }
525 if (dicts[n]->error)
526 msg_fatal("table %s:%s: query error: %m",
527 dicts[n]->type, dicts[n]->name);
528 }
529}
530
531/* postmap_header - MIME engine header call-back routine */
532
533static void postmap_header(void *ptr, int unused_header_class,
534 const HEADER_OPTS *unused_header_info,
535 VSTRING *header_buf,
536 off_t offset)
537{
538
539 /*
540 * Don't re-invent an already working wheel.
541 */
542 postmap_body(ptr, 0, STR(header_buf), LEN(header_buf), offset);
543}
544
545/* postmap_head_end - MIME engine end-of-header call-back routine */
546
547static void postmap_head_end(void *ptr)
548{
549 POSTMAP_KEY_STATE *state = (POSTMAP_KEY_STATE *) ptr;
550
551 /*
552 * Don't process the message body when we only examine primary headers.
553 */
554 state->header_done = 1;
555}
556
557/* postmap_queries - apply multiple requests from stdin */
558
559static int postmap_queries(VSTREAM *in, char **maps, const int map_count,
560 const int postmap_flags,
561 const int dict_flags)
562{
563 int found = 0;
564 VSTRING *keybuf = vstring_alloc(100);
565 DICT **dicts;
566 const char *map_name;
567 const char *value;
568 int n;
569
570 /*
571 * Sanity check.
572 */
573 if (map_count <= 0)
574 msg_panic("postmap_queries: bad map count");
575
576 /*
577 * Prepare to open maps lazily.
578 */
579 dicts = (DICT **) mymalloc(sizeof(*dicts) * map_count);
580 for (n = 0; n < map_count; n++)
581 dicts[n] = 0;
582
583 /*
584 * Perform all queries. Open maps on the fly, to avoid opening unecessary
585 * maps.
586 */
587 if ((postmap_flags & POSTMAP_FLAG_HB_KEY) == 0) {
588 while (vstring_get_nonl(keybuf, in) != VSTREAM_EOF) {
589 for (n = 0; n < map_count; n++) {
590 if (dicts[n] == 0)
591 dicts[n] = ((map_name = split_at(maps[n], ':')) != 0 ?
592 dict_open3(maps[n], map_name, O_RDONLY, dict_flags) :
593 dict_open3(var_db_type, maps[n], O_RDONLY, dict_flags));
594 if ((value = dict_get(dicts[n], STR(keybuf))) != 0) {
595 if (*value == 0) {
596 msg_warn("table %s:%s: key %s: empty string result is not allowed",
597 dicts[n]->type, dicts[n]->name, STR(keybuf));
598 msg_warn("table %s:%s should return NO RESULT in case of NOT FOUND",
599 dicts[n]->type, dicts[n]->name);
600 }
601 vstream_printf("%s %s\n", STR(keybuf), value);
602 found = 1;
603 break;
604 }
605 if (dicts[n]->error)
606 msg_fatal("table %s:%s: query error: %m",
607 dicts[n]->type, dicts[n]->name);
608 }
609 }
610 } else {
611 POSTMAP_KEY_STATE key_state;
612 MIME_STATE *mime_state;
613 int mime_errs = 0;
614
615 /*
616 * Bundle up the request and instantiate a MIME parsing engine.
617 */
618 key_state.dicts = dicts;
619 key_state.maps = maps;
620 key_state.map_count = map_count;
621 key_state.dict_flags = dict_flags;
622 key_state.header_done = 0;
623 key_state.found = 0;
624 mime_state =
625 mime_state_alloc((postmap_flags & POSTMAP_FLAG_MIME_KEY) ?
626 0 : MIME_OPT_DISABLE_MIME,
627 (postmap_flags & POSTMAP_FLAG_HEADER_KEY) ?
628 postmap_header : (MIME_STATE_HEAD_OUT) 0,
629 (postmap_flags & POSTMAP_FLAG_FULL_KEY) ?
630 (MIME_STATE_ANY_END) 0 : postmap_head_end,
631 (postmap_flags & POSTMAP_FLAG_BODY_KEY) ?
632 postmap_body : (MIME_STATE_BODY_OUT) 0,
633 (MIME_STATE_ANY_END) 0,
634 (MIME_STATE_ERR_PRINT) 0,
635 (void *) &key_state);
636
637 /*
638 * Process the input message.
639 */
640 while (vstring_get_nonl(keybuf, in) != VSTREAM_EOF
641 && key_state.header_done == 0 && mime_errs == 0)
642 mime_errs = mime_state_update(mime_state, REC_TYPE_NORM,
643 STR(keybuf), LEN(keybuf));
644
645 /*
646 * Flush the MIME engine output buffer and tidy up loose ends.
647 */
648 if (mime_errs == 0)
649 mime_errs = mime_state_update(mime_state, REC_TYPE_END, "", 0);
650 if (mime_errs)
651 msg_fatal("message format error: %s",
652 mime_state_detail(mime_errs)->text);
653 mime_state_free(mime_state);
654 found = key_state.found;
655 }
656 if (found)
657 vstream_fflush(VSTREAM_OUT);
658
659 /*
660 * Cleanup.
661 */
662 for (n = 0; n < map_count; n++)
663 if (dicts[n])
664 dict_close(dicts[n]);
665 myfree((void *) dicts);
666 vstring_free(keybuf);
667
668 return (found);
669}
670
671/* postmap_query - query a map and print the result to stdout */
672
673static int postmap_query(const char *map_type, const char *map_name,
674 const char *key, int dict_flags)
675{
676 DICT *dict;
677 const char *value;
678
679 dict = dict_open3(map_type, map_name, O_RDONLY, dict_flags);
680 if ((value = dict_get(dict, key)) != 0) {
681 if (*value == 0) {
682 msg_warn("table %s:%s: key %s: empty string result is not allowed",
683 map_type, map_name, key);
684 msg_warn("table %s:%s should return NO RESULT in case of NOT FOUND",
685 map_type, map_name);
686 }
687 vstream_printf("%s\n", value);
688 }
689 if (dict->error)
690 msg_fatal("table %s:%s: query error: %m", dict->type, dict->name);
691 vstream_fflush(VSTREAM_OUT);
692 dict_close(dict);
693 return (value != 0);
694}
695
696/* postmap_deletes - apply multiple requests from stdin */
697
698static int postmap_deletes(VSTREAM *in, char **maps, const int map_count,
699 int dict_flags)
700{
701 int found = 0;
702 VSTRING *keybuf = vstring_alloc(100);
703 DICT **dicts;
704 const char *map_name;
705 int n;
706 int open_flags;
707
708 /*
709 * Sanity check.
710 */
711 if (map_count <= 0)
712 msg_panic("postmap_deletes: bad map count");
713
714 /*
715 * Open maps ahead of time.
716 */
717 dicts = (DICT **) mymalloc(sizeof(*dicts) * map_count);
718 for (n = 0; n < map_count; n++) {
719 map_name = split_at(maps[n], ':');
720 if (map_name && strcmp(maps[n], DICT_TYPE_PROXY) == 0)
721 open_flags = O_RDWR | O_CREAT; /* XXX */
722 else
723 open_flags = O_RDWR;
724 dicts[n] = (map_name != 0 ?
725 dict_open3(maps[n], map_name, open_flags, dict_flags) :
726 dict_open3(var_db_type, maps[n], open_flags, dict_flags));
727 }
728
729 /*
730 * Perform all requests.
731 */
732 while (vstring_get_nonl(keybuf, in) != VSTREAM_EOF) {
733 for (n = 0; n < map_count; n++) {
734 found |= (dict_del(dicts[n], STR(keybuf)) == 0);
735 if (dicts[n]->error)
736 msg_fatal("table %s:%s: delete error: %m",
737 dicts[n]->type, dicts[n]->name);
738 }
739 }
740
741 /*
742 * Cleanup.
743 */
744 for (n = 0; n < map_count; n++)
745 if (dicts[n])
746 dict_close(dicts[n]);
747 myfree((void *) dicts);
748 vstring_free(keybuf);
749
750 return (found);
751}
752
753/* postmap_delete - delete a (key, value) pair from a map */
754
755static int postmap_delete(const char *map_type, const char *map_name,
756 const char *key, int dict_flags)
757{
758 DICT *dict;
759 int status;
760 int open_flags;
761
762 if (strcmp(map_type, DICT_TYPE_PROXY) == 0)
763 open_flags = O_RDWR | O_CREAT; /* XXX */
764 else
765 open_flags = O_RDWR;
766 dict = dict_open3(map_type, map_name, open_flags, dict_flags);
767 status = dict_del(dict, key);
768 if (dict->error)
769 msg_fatal("table %s:%s: delete error: %m", dict->type, dict->name);
770 dict_close(dict);
771 return (status == 0);
772}
773
774/* postmap_seq - print all map entries to stdout */
775
776static void postmap_seq(const char *map_type, const char *map_name,
777 int dict_flags)
778{
779 DICT *dict;
780 const char *key;
781 const char *value;
782 int func;
783
784 if (strcmp(map_type, DICT_TYPE_PROXY) == 0)
785 msg_fatal("can't sequence maps via the proxy service");
786 dict = dict_open3(map_type, map_name, O_RDONLY, dict_flags);
787 for (func = DICT_SEQ_FUN_FIRST; /* void */ ; func = DICT_SEQ_FUN_NEXT) {
788 if (dict_seq(dict, func, &key, &value) != 0)
789 break;
790 if (*key == 0) {
791 msg_warn("table %s:%s: empty lookup key value is not allowed",
792 map_type, map_name);
793 } else if (*value == 0) {
794 msg_warn("table %s:%s: key %s: empty string result is not allowed",
795 map_type, map_name, key);
796 msg_warn("table %s:%s should return NO RESULT in case of NOT FOUND",
797 map_type, map_name);
798 }
799 vstream_printf("%s %s\n", key, value);
800 }
801 if (dict->error)
802 msg_fatal("table %s:%s: sequence error: %m", dict->type, dict->name);
803 vstream_fflush(VSTREAM_OUT);
804 dict_close(dict);
805}
806
807/* usage - explain */
808
809static NORETURN usage(char *myname)
810{
811 msg_fatal("usage: %s [-NfinoprsuUvw] [-c config_dir] [-d key] [-q key] [map_type:]file...",
812 myname);
813}
814
815MAIL_VERSION_STAMP_DECLARE;
816
817int main(int argc, char **argv)
818{
819 char *path_name;
820 int ch;
821 int fd;
822 char *slash;
823 struct stat st;
824 int postmap_flags = POSTMAP_FLAG_AS_OWNER | POSTMAP_FLAG_SAVE_PERM;
825 int open_flags = O_RDWR | O_CREAT | O_TRUNC;
826 int dict_flags = (DICT_FLAG_DUP_WARN | DICT_FLAG_FOLD_FIX
827 | DICT_FLAG_UTF8_REQUEST);
828 char *query = 0;
829 char *delkey = 0;
830 int sequence = 0;
831 int found;
832 int force_utf8 = 0;
833
834 /*
835 * Fingerprint executables and core dumps.
836 */
837 MAIL_VERSION_STAMP_ALLOCATE;
838
839 /*
840 * Be consistent with file permissions.
841 */
842 umask(022);
843
844 /*
845 * To minimize confusion, make sure that the standard file descriptors
846 * are open before opening anything else. XXX Work around for 44BSD where
847 * fstat can return EBADF on an open file descriptor.
848 */
849 for (fd = 0; fd < 3; fd++)
850 if (fstat(fd, &st) == -1
851 && (close(fd), open("/dev/null", O_RDWR, 0)) != fd)
852 msg_fatal("open /dev/null: %m");
853
854 /*
855 * Process environment options as early as we can. We are not set-uid,
856 * and we are supposed to be running in a controlled environment.
857 */
858 if (getenv(CONF_ENV_VERB))
859 msg_verbose = 1;
860
861 /*
862 * Initialize. Set up logging, read the global configuration file and
863 * extract configuration information.
864 */
865 if ((slash = strrchr(argv[0], '/')) != 0 && slash[1])
866 argv[0] = slash + 1;
867 msg_vstream_init(argv[0], VSTREAM_ERR);
868 msg_syslog_init(mail_task(argv[0]), LOG_PID, LOG_FACILITY);
869
870 /*
871 * Check the Postfix library version as soon as we enable logging.
872 */
873 MAIL_VERSION_CHECK;
874
875 /*
876 * Parse JCL.
877 */
878 while ((ch = GETOPT(argc, argv, "Nbc:d:fhimnopq:rsuUvw")) > 0) {
879 switch (ch) {
880 default:
881 usage(argv[0]);
882 break;
883 case 'N':
884 dict_flags |= DICT_FLAG_TRY1NULL;
885 dict_flags &= ~DICT_FLAG_TRY0NULL;
886 break;
887 case 'b':
888 postmap_flags |= POSTMAP_FLAG_BODY_KEY;
889 break;
890 case 'c':
891 if (setenv(CONF_ENV_PATH, optarg, 1) < 0)
892 msg_fatal("out of memory");
893 break;
894 case 'd':
895 if (sequence || query || delkey)
896 msg_fatal("specify only one of -s -q or -d");
897 delkey = optarg;
898 break;
899 case 'f':
900 dict_flags &= ~DICT_FLAG_FOLD_FIX;
901 break;
902 case 'h':
903 postmap_flags |= POSTMAP_FLAG_HEADER_KEY;
904 break;
905 case 'i':
906 open_flags &= ~O_TRUNC;
907 break;
908 case 'm':
909 postmap_flags |= POSTMAP_FLAG_MIME_KEY;
910 break;
911 case 'n':
912 dict_flags |= DICT_FLAG_TRY0NULL;
913 dict_flags &= ~DICT_FLAG_TRY1NULL;
914 break;
915 case 'o':
916 postmap_flags &= ~POSTMAP_FLAG_AS_OWNER;
917 break;
918 case 'p':
919 postmap_flags &= ~POSTMAP_FLAG_SAVE_PERM;
920 break;
921 case 'q':
922 if (sequence || query || delkey)
923 msg_fatal("specify only one of -s -q or -d");
924 query = optarg;
925 break;
926 case 'r':
927 dict_flags &= ~(DICT_FLAG_DUP_WARN | DICT_FLAG_DUP_IGNORE);
928 dict_flags |= DICT_FLAG_DUP_REPLACE;
929 break;
930 case 's':
931 if (query || delkey)
932 msg_fatal("specify only one of -s or -q or -d");
933 sequence = 1;
934 break;
935 case 'u':
936 dict_flags &= ~DICT_FLAG_UTF8_REQUEST;
937 break;
938 case 'U':
939 force_utf8 = 1;
940 break;
941 case 'v':
942 msg_verbose++;
943 break;
944 case 'w':
945 dict_flags &= ~(DICT_FLAG_DUP_WARN | DICT_FLAG_DUP_REPLACE);
946 dict_flags |= DICT_FLAG_DUP_IGNORE;
947 break;
948 }
949 }
950 mail_conf_read();
951 /* Re-evaluate mail_task() after reading main.cf. */
952 msg_syslog_init(mail_task(argv[0]), LOG_PID, LOG_FACILITY);
953 mail_dict_init();
954 if ((query == 0 || strcmp(query, "-") != 0)
955 && (postmap_flags & POSTMAP_FLAG_ANY_KEY))
956 msg_fatal("specify -b -h or -m only with \"-q -\"");
957 if ((postmap_flags & POSTMAP_FLAG_ANY_KEY) != 0
958 && (postmap_flags & POSTMAP_FLAG_ANY_KEY)
959 == (postmap_flags & POSTMAP_FLAG_MIME_KEY))
960 msg_warn("ignoring -m option without -b or -h");
961 if ((postmap_flags & (POSTMAP_FLAG_ANY_KEY & ~POSTMAP_FLAG_MIME_KEY))
962 && force_utf8 == 0)
963 dict_flags &= ~DICT_FLAG_UTF8_MASK;
964
965 /*
966 * Use the map type specified by the user, or fall back to a default
967 * database type.
968 */
969 if (delkey) { /* remove entry */
970 if (optind + 1 > argc)
971 usage(argv[0]);
972 if (strcmp(delkey, "-") == 0)
973 exit(postmap_deletes(VSTREAM_IN, argv + optind, argc - optind,
974 dict_flags | DICT_FLAG_LOCK) == 0);
975 found = 0;
976 while (optind < argc) {
977 if ((path_name = split_at(argv[optind], ':')) != 0) {
978 found |= postmap_delete(argv[optind], path_name, delkey,
979 dict_flags | DICT_FLAG_LOCK);
980 } else {
981 found |= postmap_delete(var_db_type, argv[optind], delkey,
982 dict_flags | DICT_FLAG_LOCK);
983 }
984 optind++;
985 }
986 exit(found ? 0 : 1);
987 } else if (query) { /* query map(s) */
988 if (optind + 1 > argc)
989 usage(argv[0]);
990 if (strcmp(query, "-") == 0)
991 exit(postmap_queries(VSTREAM_IN, argv + optind, argc - optind,
992 postmap_flags, dict_flags | DICT_FLAG_LOCK) == 0);
993 while (optind < argc) {
994 if ((path_name = split_at(argv[optind], ':')) != 0) {
995 found = postmap_query(argv[optind], path_name, query,
996 dict_flags | DICT_FLAG_LOCK);
997 } else {
998 found = postmap_query(var_db_type, argv[optind], query,
999 dict_flags | DICT_FLAG_LOCK);
1000 }
1001 if (found)
1002 exit(0);
1003 optind++;
1004 }
1005 exit(1);
1006 } else if (sequence) {
1007 while (optind < argc) {
1008 if ((path_name = split_at(argv[optind], ':')) != 0) {
1009 postmap_seq(argv[optind], path_name,
1010 dict_flags | DICT_FLAG_LOCK);
1011 } else {
1012 postmap_seq(var_db_type, argv[optind],
1013 dict_flags | DICT_FLAG_LOCK);
1014 }
1015 exit(0);
1016 }
1017 exit(1);
1018 } else { /* create/update map(s) */
1019 if (optind + 1 > argc)
1020 usage(argv[0]);
1021 while (optind < argc) {
1022 if ((path_name = split_at(argv[optind], ':')) != 0) {
1023 postmap(argv[optind], path_name, postmap_flags,
1024 open_flags, dict_flags);
1025 } else {
1026 postmap(var_db_type, argv[optind], postmap_flags,
1027 open_flags, dict_flags);
1028 }
1029 optind++;
1030 }
1031 exit(0);
1032 }
1033}
